{{Infobox book | name=The Girl Who Played Go | image=The Girl Who Played Go book cover.JPG | caption=2003 English Translation Cover | authors=Shan Sa, translated by Adriana Hunter | illustrator= | cover_artist= | country=France | language=French, translated to English | series= | subject= | genre= | published= 2001, English translation 2003 | media_type=Print | pages=280 pp | isbn=0-099-49079-X | oclc= | dewey= | congress= | preceded_by= | followed_by= }}
'''''The Girl Who Played Go''''' is a 2001 French novel, original published as ''La Joueuse de Go'', by [[Shan Sa]] set during the Japanese occupation of [[Manchukuo|Manchuria]]. It tells the story of a 16-year-old Chinese girl who is exceptionally good at the game of [[Go (game)|Go]], and her games with a young Japanese officer. It was translated into English in 2003<ref> Bantick, Christopher [http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2003/05/16/1052885399939.html The Girl Who Played Go May 17, 2003] ''[[Sydney Morning Herald]]'' Retrieved September 10, 2015 </ref> and has been translated into 32 languages in total.<ref> [https://fr.linkedin.com/pub/shan-sa/34/358/307 Shan Sa LinkedIn page]{{Dead link|date=June 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=no }} Retrieved September 10, 2015 </ref>
The novel won a number of prizes, including the [[Prix Goncourt des Lycéens]] (Prix Goncourt of the High-school students) in 2001 and the [[Kiriyama Prize]] for fiction in 2004.<ref> [http://www.kiriyamaprize.org/winners/2004/index%28winnew%29.shtml Kiriyama Prize - 2004 Winners and Finalists] Retrieved September 10, 2015 </ref>
